<h3 align=center style='text-align:center'>Figure 5</h3>

<h3 align=center style='text-align:center'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></h3>

<h3><span style='font-weight:normal;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold'>Generating 64
bit inputs (A and B) is a special case, thus you must use the rand64 component
to generate their values.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Why are we not
able to just simply use randv and set WIDTH = 64?<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>This will not work because the INTEGER data
type in VHDL does not support integers larger than 32 bits.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>So that we can fully test our ALU, this
problem was solved by concatenating the outputs of two 32-bit generators that
are seeded differently.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Look at the VHDL
for rand64 to see the implementation for yourself.<o:p></o:p></span></h3>

<p align=center style='margin-left:.5in;text-align:center'><a href="Logic.html">Click
here to proceed</a></p>

